  "text": "The molecular bases of sleep regulation are not completely understood. Tantalizingly, recent work indicates that calcium-dependent hyperpolarization is critical to sleep duration, and that sleep deterioration is associated with impairment of calcium-dependent potassium channels, voltage-gated calcium channels (VGCC), and Nmethyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) glutamate receptors [CITATION_1] . Since both hyperpolarization linked to calcium dyshomeostasis and NMDA receptor-related hyperexcitability were documented in Prnp ablated mice (discussed in the next section), loss of PrP C -dependent control of these ion channels may underlie the sleep disruption in PrP Cdeficient mice and perhaps also in prion diseases.",
